'''Nuno Miguel da Costa Jóia''' ({{IPA|pt|ˈnu.nu mi.ˈɡɛl dɐ ˈkɔʃ.tɐ ˈʒɔ.jɐ|lang}}; born 10 February 1991), known as '''Nuno da Costa''', is a Cape Verdean professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] or [[Winger (association football)|winger]] for [[Süper Lig]] club [[İstanbul Başakşehir F.K.|İstanbul Başakşehir]] and the [[Cape Verde national football team|Cape Verde national team]].

Raised in France, he began his senior career with [[Aubagne FC|Aubagne]] in the [[Championnat National 3|fifth tier]] before moving to [[Valenciennes FC|Valenciennes]] of Ligue 2 in 2015. Two years later he debuted in [[Ligue 1]] with [[RC Strasbourg|Strasbourg]], where he won the [[Coupe de la Ligue]] in 2019. In January 2020, he signed for [[Nottingham Forest]].

Da Costa scored on his senior international debut for [[Cape Verde national football team|Cape Verde]] in June 2016.

==Club career==
===Early career===
Born in [[Praia]], Cape Verde, Da Costa was raised in Portugal from 1993 and began playing with U.R. Mercês in Lisbon. He then moved to [[Aubagne]] in southern France, where he started his senior career with Aubagne FC in France's [[Championnat National 3|fifth tier]].<ref name=u10/>

On 4 January 2014, Da Costa scored the opening goal of a 3–3 draw at home to [[Ligue 2]] club [[Dijon FCO]] in the last 64 of the [[Coupe de France]], losing on penalties.<ref name=u10>{{cite news |title=Nuno Da Costa : Oser rêver, c'est le premier pas vers la réussite |trans-title=Daring to dream, that's the first step towards success|url=http://ultimodiez.fr/2018/02/03/nuno-da-costa-oser-rever-cest-le-premier-pas-pour-le-realiser/ |access-date=10 March 2020 |publisher=U10 |date=3 February 2018 |language=fr}}</ref>

===Valenciennes===
Da Costa joined [[Valenciennes FC]] of Ligue 2 on 3 August 2015, following a season of 14 goals and eight assists.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Penland |first1=Erwann |title=Valenciennes : Un talent de CFA2, CV PRO, s'engage|trans-title=Valenciennes: A CFA2 talent, with a PRO CV, signs|url=http://www.foot-national.com/foot-valenciennes-un-talent-de-cfa2-cv-pro-s-engage-73862.html |access-date=10 March 2020 |publisher=Foot National |date=3 August 2015 |language=fr}}</ref> In his first professional season, he scored ten goals, including two on 6 May 2016 in a 4–1 win away to relegated [[Paris FC]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pruneta |first1=Laurent |title=Ligue 2: Le Paris FC rate ses adieux, corrigé par Valenciennes (1–4)|trans-title=Ligue 2: Paris FC mess up their goodbye, corrected by Valenciennes (1–4) |url=http://www.leparisien.fr/sports/football/ligue-2-le-paris-fc-rate-ses-adieux-corrige-par-valenciennes-1-4-06-05-2016-5773493.php |access-date=10 March 2020 |work=[[Le Parisien]] |date=6 May 2016 |language=fr}}</ref> He followed this with nine more in his second year, including a brace in a 3–3 home draw with [[FC Bourg-Peronnas]] on 18 November.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gotte |first1=Richard |title=LIGUE 2 Valenciennes trop fébrile pour conclure|trans-title=LIGUE 2 Valenciennes too feverish to wrap it up|url=https://www.lavoixdunord.fr/76216/article/2016-11-18/valenciennes-trop-febrile-pour-conclure |access-date=10 March 2020 |work=[[La Voix du Nord (daily)|La Voix du Nord]] |date=18 November 2016 |language=fr}}</ref>

===Strasbourg===
On 3 July 2017, Da Costa signed a four-year deal with [[Ligue 1]] club [[RC Strasbourg]], replacing [[Khalid Boutaïb]] who had left for [[Malatyaspor]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Nuno Da Costa (Valenciennes) signe à Strasbourg|trans-title=Nuno Da Costa (Valenciennes) signs for Strasbourg |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Nuno-da-costa-valenciennes-signe-a-strasbourg/815556 |access-date=10 March 2020 |work=[[L'Équipe]] |date=3 July 2017 |language=fr}}</ref> In his first top-flight season he found the net five times, including both goals of a 2–1 win at [[OGC Nice]] on 22 October that earned him a place in ''[[L'Équipe]]''{{'}}s team of the week.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stratmann |first1=Edward |title=Strasbourg's Nuno da Costa Has Been On A Fascinating Road To Top Flight Football |url=https://www.thesportsman.com/articles/strasbourgs-nuno-da-costa-has-been-on-a-fascinating-road-to-top-flight-football |access-date=10 March 2020 |publisher=The Sportsman |date=28 October 2017}}</ref> On 4 November, he was sent off after half an hour of a 2–0 loss at [[Troyes AC]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Thierry Laurey (Strasbourg) regrette le carton rouge "très sévère" de Da Costa contre Troyes|trans-title=Thierry Laurey (Strasbourg) regrets Da Costa's "very strict" red card against Troyes |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Thierry-laurey-strasbourg-regrette-le-carton-rouge-tres-severe-de-da-costa-contre-troyes/848191 |access-date=10 March 2020 |work=L'Équipe |date=4 November 2017 |language=fr}}</ref>

Da Costa was an 81st-minute substitute for [[Lebo Mothiba]] as they won the [[2019 Coupe de la Ligue Final]] on penalties against [[EA Guingamp]] on 30 March.<ref name=ligue>{{cite news |last1=Loisy |first1=Guillaume |title=Vainqueur de la Coupe de la Ligue, Strasbourg grimpe au 7e ciel|trans-title=Coupe de la Ligue winners, Strasbourg climb to 7th heaven |url=https://sport24.lefigaro.fr/football/live/coupe-de-la-ligue/2018/1046530/strasbourg-guingamp |access-date=10 March 2020 |work=[[Le Figaro]] |date=30 March 2019 |language=fr}}</ref> Four days later, he scored twice in a 4–0 win over [[Stade Reims]] at the [[Stade de la Meinau]], part of his eight of the season.<ref>{{cite news |title=30e journée de Ligue 1: Festival offensif de Strasbourg contre Reims avec des doublés d'Anthony Goncalves et Nuno Da Costa (4-0)|trans-title=30th matchday of Ligue 1: Attacking festival for Strasbourg against Reims with braces from Anthony Goncalves and Nuno Da Costa (4-0)  |url=https://www.20minutes.fr/sport/football/2488599-20190403-30e-journee-de-ligue-1-festival-offensif-de-strasbourg-contre-reims-avec-des-doubles-d-anthony-goncalves-et-nuno-da-costa-4-0 |access-date=10 March 2020 |work=[[20 minutes (France)|20 minutes]] |language=fr}}</ref> After that game, former France international [[Daniel Bravo]] described Da Costa's goal as "not bad for a black guy" during his [[beIN Sports]] punditry; he apologised in person for offence caused to the player, who accepted the apology.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rathborn |first1=Jack |title=Daniel Bravo: Former France international describes Nuno da Costa's goal as 'not bad for a black guy' following Moise Kean race storm |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/nuno-da-costa-daniel-bravo-moise-kean-leonardo-bonucci-ligue-1-psg-strasbourg-reims-a8854541.html |access-date=10 March 2020 |work=[[The Independent]] |date=4 April 2019}}</ref>

===Nottingham Forest===
On 29 January 2020, Da Costa joined [[EFL Championship]] club [[Nottingham Forest]]. The length and cost of the deal was not disclosed.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nuno da Costa: Nottingham Forest sign Strasbourg striker for an undisclosed fee |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51295379 |access-date=10 March 2020 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=29 January 2020}}</ref> He debuted on 11 February in a 1–0 home loss to [[Charlton Athletic]], playing the last twenty minutes in place of [[Ryan Yates]]; days later he was injured in an under-23 game against [[Crewe Alexandra]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bonell |first1=Jonny |last2=Wakefield |first2=Mark |title=Da Costa injury latest as Nottingham Forest boss sent message ahead of crucial clash |url=https://nottinghampost.com/sport/football/transfer-news/forest-transfers-news-da-costa-3846443 |access-date=10 March 2020 |work=[[Nottingham Post]] |date=14 February 2020}}</ref>

Da Costa was loaned to [[Belgian First Division A]] side [[Royal Excel Mouscron]] for the season on 5 October 2020, with the option to make the deal permanent.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nottingham Forest transfer news: Cafu joins from Olympiakos |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54422914 |access-date=21 October 2021 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=5 October 2020}}</ref> He scored six goals during his stint, including both of a 2–2 home draw with [[OH Leuven]] on 15 December.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jupiler Pro League: Charleroi renverse le Cercle de Bruges dans un match fou, Mouscron tient OHL en échec|trans-title=Jupiler Pro League: Charleroi come back against Cercle Bruges in a crazy match, Mouscron keep OHL in check|url=https://www.rtl.be/sport/football/football-belgique/jupiler-pro-league-charleroi-renverse-le-cercle-de-bruges-dans-un-match-fou-mouscron-tient-ohl-en-echec-1266078.aspx |access-date=21 October 2021 |publisher=[[RTL Group]] |date=15 December 2020 |language=French}}</ref>

On 31 August 2021, Da Costa was loaned out again for a year, returning to the French Ligue 2 at [[Stade Malherbe Caen|Caen]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Curtis |first1=Leigh |title=Nottingham Forest confirm double departure on transfer deadline day |url=https://www.nottinghampost.com/sport/football/football-news/forest-arter-transfers-da-costa-5854197 |access-date=21 October 2021 |work=Nottingham Post |date=31 August 2021}}</ref>

===Auxerre===
On 5 August 2022, Da Costa joined [[Ligue 1]] side [[AJ Auxerre]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.aja.fr/nuno-da-costa-nouveau-ndeg9-de-laja | title=Nuno da Costa nouveau n°9 de l'AJA ! | date=5 August 2022 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/2022/august/05/da-costa-departs/ | title=Da Costa departs to Auxerre }}</ref>

=== Kasımpaşa ===
On 12 September 2023, Da Costa signed for Turkish [[Süper Lig]] side [[Kasımpaşa S.K.|Kasımpaşa]]. The duration of the contract and transfer fee were both undisclosed.<ref>{{Cite web |last= |first= |date=12 September 2023 |title=Nuno Da Costa Kasımpaşamızda |trans-title=Nuno Da Costa is in our Kasımpaşa |url=http://www.kasimpasa.com.tr/tr/haberler/a-takim-haberleri/nuno-da-costa-kasimpasamizda_5519.html |access-date= |website= |publisher=Kasımpaşa |language=tr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last= |first= |date=12 September 2023 |title=Nuno Da Costa rejoint Kasimpasa |trans-title=Nuno Da Costa joins Kasimpasa |url=https://www.aja.fr/nuno-da-costa-rejoint-kasimpasa/ |access-date= |website= |publisher=Auxerre |language=fr-FR}}</ref>

==International career==
Da Costa made his international debut for [[Cape Verde national football team|Cape Verde]] on 4 June 2016 in a [[2017 Africa Cup of Nations qualification]] match away to [[São Tomé and Príncipe national football team|São Tomé and Príncipe]]. He came on in the 73rd minute for [[Garry Rodrigues]], and six minutes later scored in a 2–1 win.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nuno da Costa: "A estreia não poderia ter sido melhor"|trans-title=Nuno da Costa: "The debut could not have been better" |url=https://dtudo1pouco.com/nuno-da-costa-a-estreia-nao-poderia-ter-sido-melhor/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211019014520/https://dtudo1pouco.com/nuno-da-costa-a-estreia-nao-poderia-ter-sido-melhor/ |url-status=usurped |archive-date=19 October 2021 |access-date=10 March 2020 |publisher=D Tudo 1 Pouco |date=7 June 2016 |language=pt}}</ref> He did not play again until the return of manager [[Rui Águas (footballer)|Rui Águas]] on 9 September 2018, in a 1–1 draw away to Lesotho in the unsuccessful [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations qualification]] campaign.<ref>{{cite news |title=Futebol/CAN´2019: Cabo Verde empata com Lesoto na re-estreia oficial de Rui Águas e continua no último lugar do grupo|trans-title=Football/ACN'2019: Cape Verde draw with Lesotho on Rui Águas' second debut and continue in last place in the group |url=https://inforpress.cv/futebol-can2019-cabo-verde-empata-com-lesoto-na-re-estreia-oficial-de-rui-aguas-e-continua-no-ultimo-lugar-do-grupo/ |access-date=21 October 2021 |publisher=[[Inforpress]] |date=9 September 2018 |language=Portuguese}}</ref>

